---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import HStarMotif from "../components/HStarMotif.astro";
import { CONTENT_POINTS } from "../data/content-points";
import { peelLayers } from "../lib/geometry/hull";
import { relatedIndices, edgesFromNeighbors, MIN_POINTS_FOR_DELAUNAY } from "../lib/geometry/related";
import { buildAdjacency, findMinimumZeroForcingSet } from "../lib/zeroForcing";

const workLayers = peelLayers(CONTENT_POINTS, (p) => [p.recency, p.depth]);
const orderedWorkCount = workLayers.reduce((n, layer) => n + layer.length, 0);

const delaunayEdges = edgesFromNeighbors(relatedIndices(CONTENT_POINTS.map((p) => [p.topic, p.recency])));
const delaunayActive = CONTENT_POINTS.length >= MIN_POINTS_FOR_DELAUNAY;

const zfGraph = buildAdjacency(
  CONTENT_POINTS.map((p) => p.slug),
  delaunayEdges.map(([a, b]) => [CONTENT_POINTS[a].slug, CONTENT_POINTS[b].slug]),
);
const zfSeeds = findMinimumZeroForcingSet(zfGraph);
---

<BaseLayout
  title="How This Site Works — Ethan Luh"
  description="Notes on the math and geometry driving this site: zero forcing, convex hull peeling, and Delaunay triangulation."
>
  <section class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6 py-10 scroll-mt-16">
    <h2 class="font-display text-h3 border-l-2 border-moss pl-4 mb-6">How This Site Works</h2>
    <p class="font-mono text-xs text-stone mb-6">
      Notes on the math driving the layout and animation of this site — not a project write-up, just what's
      actually running under the hood.
    </p>
    <div class="flex flex-col gap-8">
      <div id="zero-forcing" class="reveal flex flex-col sm:flex-row gap-6 items-start sm:items-center scroll-mt-24">
        <p class="font-mono text-xs text-stone shrink-0 sm:w-40">
          {zfSeeds.length} seed{zfSeeds.length === 1 ? "" : "s"} · {CONTENT_POINTS.length} nodes
        </p>
        <p class="text-parchment/90 max-w-md">
          The hero graph on the homepage is this site's actual content — the same {CONTENT_POINTS.length} items,
          connected by the same Delaunay edges used for "related" — animated by <strong>zero forcing</strong>, the
          color-change rule from the zero forcing research: a colored vertex with exactly one uncolored neighbor
          forces it to color. The {zfSeeds.length} moss-colored seeds on load are a real computed minimum zero
          forcing set, not a hand-picked example; everything else propagates in the order the rule actually forces
          it. It's a live instance of the math, not an illustration of it — hover a node for its title, click to
          visit.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="reveal flex flex-col sm:flex-row gap-6 items-start sm:items-center">
        <HStarMotif vectorId="cube4" mode="bar" width={160} height={40} class="shrink-0" />
        <p class="text-parchment/90 max-w-md">
          The bars above are the h*-vector of the 4-cube, <span class="font-mono text-xs text-stone">(1, 11, 11, 1)</span> —
          a classical Ehrhart theory example (an Eulerian number sequence), kept here purely as a textbook
          illustration, distinct from the zero forcing hero above, which renders real content data. Once the zero
          forcing polytope result with Hanely is finalized, this slot gets reassigned to that h*-vector specifically.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="reveal flex flex-col sm:flex-row gap-6 items-start sm:items-center">
        <p class="font-mono text-xs text-stone shrink-0 sm:w-40">
          {workLayers.length} layer{workLayers.length === 1 ? "" : "s"} · {orderedWorkCount} items
        </p>
        <p class="text-parchment/90 max-w-md">
          Work on the homepage isn't grouped by type (research/project/experience) — it's ordered by convex-hull
          peel layer over (recency, depth). The Featured card is the top of layer 0, the Pareto-extreme set not
          dominated on both axes by any other single item; everything else follows in layer order, labeled with its
          kind and layer number.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="reveal flex flex-col sm:flex-row gap-6 items-start sm:items-center">
        <p class="font-mono text-xs text-stone shrink-0 sm:w-40">
          {CONTENT_POINTS.length} points{delaunayActive ? "" : " (below threshold)"}
        </p>
        <p class="text-parchment/90 max-w-md">
          The small node-and-edge diagram next to each "related" list is the actual Delaunay triangulation over
          hand-placed (topic, recency) coordinates — every point and edge in the full graph, with the current
          card's node and its neighbors highlighted. Below {MIN_POINTS_FOR_DELAUNAY} points the triangulation gets
          arbitrary, so the feature stays off until there's enough content to make it mean something.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>

<script>
  const reveals = document.querySelectorAll<HTMLElement>(".reveal");
  const prefersReducedMotion = window.matchMedia("(prefers-reduced-motion: reduce)").matches;

  if (prefersReducedMotion) {
    reveals.forEach((el) => el.classList.add("in-view"));
  } else {
    const observer = new IntersectionObserver(
      (entries) => {
        for (const entry of entries) {
          if (entry.isIntersecting) {
            entry.target.classList.add("in-view");
            observer.unobserve(entry.target);
          }
        }
      },
      { threshold: 0.1 },
    );
    reveals.forEach((el) => observer.observe(el));
  }
</script>

<style>
  .reveal {
    opacity: 0;
    transform: translateY(12px);
    transition:
      opacity var(--duration-base, 300ms) var(--ease-field),
      transform var(--duration-base, 300ms) var(--ease-field);
  }
  .reveal.in-view {
    opacity: 1;
    transform: translateY(0);
  }
  .reveal.in-view :global(.hstar-draw .hstar-stroke) {
    stroke-dashoffset: 0;
  }
  .reveal.in-view :global(.hstar-draw .hstar-dot) {
    opacity: 1;
    transform: scale(1);
  }
  .reveal.in-view :global(.hstar-draw .hstar-fill) {
    opacity: 1;
  }
</style>
